<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFDEBAC7A8745B554" box="[526,544,790,815]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">c.</emphasis>
52% instead of 42% (females) and 44% (males)in 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFE28AC5A8758B534" baseAuthorityName="Paulucci" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[461,573,822,847]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="zopissa">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFE28AC5A8758B534" box="[461,573,822,847]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. zopissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. For example, the shell of a male of 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFEB3AC3A84BCB514" authority="Boeters &amp; Falkner, 2017" authorityName="Boeters &amp; Falkner" authorityYear="2017" box="[342,473,854,879]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="corsensis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFEB3AC3A84BCB514" box="[342,473,854,879]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. corsensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6E9A57E5E604FF9DFE07AC3A8747B50B" box="[482,546,854,880]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
showed the following measurements: height 
<quantity id="80259B69E604FF9DFE51AC198744B5F4" box="[436,545,885,911]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="2.9">2.90 mm</quantity>
, diameter 
<quantity id="80259B69E604FF9DFD78AC198663B5F4" box="[669,774,885,912]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="2.05">2.05 mm</quantity>
and height of aperture to total height of 51.6%. Further, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFEEEACD984F4B5B5" authority="Boeters &amp; Falkner, 2017" authorityName="Boeters &amp; Falkner" authorityYear="2017" box="[267,401,949,974]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="corsensis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFEEEACD984F4B5B5" box="[267,401,949,974]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. corsensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6E9A57E5E604FF9DFE7FACD984BEB5B4" box="[410,475,949,975]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the last whorl before the aperture neither descends nor ascends, in 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFD8CACB987B9B595" baseAuthorityName="Paulucci" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[617,732,981,1006]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="zopissa">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFD8CACB987B9B595" box="[617,732,981,1006]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. zopissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the last whorl often descends clearly immediately before the aperture, as can be deduced, for example, even from the frontal view in 
<figureCitation id="DFE62A09E604FF9DFECBAB5884D1B235" box="[302,436,1076,1102]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[131,142,1871,1889]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,216,1814]" captionTargetId="figure-17@21.[132,1455,215,1840]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 11. — A-C, Mercuria meridionalis (Risso, 1826), France, Var, Foux de Draguignan, leg. Boeters 27.IX.1969, BOE 2414 ex 0261 (A, B); BOE 2151 ex 0261 (C); A, ♀; B, ♂; C, ♂, pallial tentacle, copulatory organ and pedal lobe clearly to be seen; D, E, Mercuria sp., presumable topotypes of Bithinia [sic] moutonii Dupuy, 1849; D, France, Alpes-Maritimes, Cannes (i.e. Mandelieu-la-Napoule [Népoule sensu Dupuy]), ♀ (MNHN-LOC); E, France, Var, Grasse (MNHN-JOU); F, Mercuria corsensis n. sp. France, Corse-du-Sud, Bonifacio, Couvent de la Trinité, leg Boeters IX.1979 (holotype MNHN-IM-2000-31951 ex BOE 0916); G-H, Mercuria zopissa (Paulucci, 1882), Italy, Sardinia, Monte dei Sette Fratelli, leg Giusti, Topotypes ex SMF 252038/7; G, globular shell; H, slender shell; I-J, Pseudamnicola emiliana (Paladilhe 1869); I, Neotype ex Topotype; France, Hérault, ruisseau [d’eaux douces] près de Balaruc (MNHN-IM-2000-32541 ex de Folin); J, de Folin’s label [“determ. par Paladilhe”, handwriting de Folin]. Scale bars: A, B, D-I, 3 mm; C, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5154189" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5154189/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">Fig. 11H. A</figureCitation>
character which discriminates 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFF61AB398423B215" authority="Boeters &amp; Falkner, 2017" authorityName="Boeters &amp; Falkner" authorityYear="2017" box="[132,326,1109,1134]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="corsensis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFF61AB398423B215" box="[132,326,1109,1134]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">Mercuria corsensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6E9A57E5E604FF9DFEA9AB3984EDB214" box="[332,392,1109,1135]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
as well as 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFE1DAB39870DB215" baseAuthorityName="Paulucci" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[504,616,1109,1134]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="zopissa">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFE1DAB39870DB215" box="[504,616,1109,1134]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. zopissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFF66AB19845CB2F5" box="[131,313,1140,1166]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFF66AB198582B2F5" box="[131,231,1141,1166]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">Mercuria</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
is the shallow suture in combination with the ovate shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0FC76507E604FF9DFF61ABB88692B76A" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4762368CE604FF9DFF61ABB8858DB297" blockId="24.[130,777,1236,2028]" box="[132,232,1236,1262]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4762368CE604FF9DFF61AB9F849CB190" blockId="24.[130,777,1236,2028]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">
The new species has been considered by 
<bibRefCitation id="234C4B7DE604FF9DFDD5AB9F85CFB355" author="FALKNER G. &amp; RIPKEN TH &amp; FALKNER M." pageId="24" pageNumber="251" pagination="1 - 350" refId="ref25632" refString="FALKNER G., RIPKEN TH. E. J. &amp; FALKNER M. 2002. - Mollusques continentaux de France. Liste de Reference annotee et Bibliographie. Patrimoines naturels 52: 1 - 350." type="journal article" year="2002">
Falkner 
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFD62AB9887DCB376" box="[647,697,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">et al.</emphasis>
(2002: 79)
</bibRefCitation>
as conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFE75AA788662B355" authority="(Paulucci, 1882)" baseAuthorityName="Paulucci" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[400,775,1299,1326]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="zopissa">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFE75AA788726B356" box="[400,579,1300,1325]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">Mercuria zopissa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="234C4B7DE604FF9DFDB1AA7F879AB355" author="PAULUCCI M." box="[596,767,1299,1326]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" refId="ref28065" refString="PAULUCCI M. 1882. - Note malacologiche sulla Fauna terrestre e fluviale dell'isola di Sardegna. Bullettino della Societa malacologica italiana 8 (1882) (2): 139 - 256, (3): 257 - 381; pls 1 - 9 [plates delivered with vol. 9 (1883)] [Separatum: Siena, Bargellini (1882): I-VII + 1 - 247, pls 1 - 9.] Available online at: https: // gdz. sub. uni-goettingen. de /" type="url" year="1882">Paulucci, 1882</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from Sardinia, but a new evaluation of its characters led us to acknowledge it as a distinct species. Judging from the nevertheless existing striking morphological similarities, 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFF63AAF8859EB3D6" baseAuthorityName="Paulucci" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[134,251,1428,1453]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="zopissa">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFF63AAF8859EB3D6" box="[134,251,1428,1453]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. zopissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFED0AAF884D2B3D6" authority="Boeters &amp; Falkner, 2017" authorityName="Boeters &amp; Falkner" authorityYear="2017" box="[309,439,1428,1453]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="corsensis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFED0AAF884D2B3D6" box="[309,439,1428,1453]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. corsensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6E9A57E5E604FF9DFE24AAF88765B3D5" box="[449,512,1428,1454]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
must be considered as closely related sister species. This means they form a group which is differentiated with a significant gap against all other 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFF67AA9F8583B077" box="[130,230,1523,1548]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFF67AA9F8583B077" box="[130,230,1523,1548]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">Mercuria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-species of 
<collectingCountry id="3FCA761CE604FF9DFE81AA9F84CBB076" box="[356,430,1523,1549]" name="France" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">France</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="3FCA761CE604FF9DFE0EAA9F874BB076" box="[491,558,1523,1549]" name="Spain" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">Spain</collectingCountry>
. As they are exclusively confined to 
<collectingCountry id="3FCA761CE604FF9DFEB4A97E84C1B057" box="[337,420,1554,1580]" name="France" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">Corsica</collectingCountry>
and Sardinia it can be assumed that their evolution is correlated to the well known Tertiary plate tectonics and the complex palaeogeographic history of the two islands (as for example outlined with instructive maps in de 
<bibRefCitation id="234C4B7DE604FF9DFEE0A9FF848FB0D7" author="JONG H. &amp; DE" box="[261,490,1682,1709]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" pagination="99 - 164" refId="ref26884" refString="JONG H. DE 1998. - In search of historical biogeographic patterns in the western Mediterranean terrestrial fauna. Biological Journal of the linnean Society 65 (2): 99 - 164. Available online at: http: // www. onlinelibrary. wiley. com [Article ID. bj 980239]" type="journal article" year="1998">Jong 1998: 113-118</bibRefCitation>
). They must share a common ancestral species which lived on the Corso-Sardinan microplate when it became separated from the South European continental margin. As the distance between the northernmost occurrences of 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFE24A87E8749B150" baseAuthorityName="Paulucci" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[449,556,1810,1835]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="zopissa">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFE24A87E8749B150" box="[449,556,1810,1835]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. zopissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the 
<typeStatus id="9866882EE604FF9DFD63A87E87D0B157" box="[646,693,1810,1836]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="80DD4D0FE604FF9DFF47A85E8444B130" authority="Boeters &amp; Falkner, 2017" authorityName="Boeters &amp; Falkner" authorityYear="2017" box="[162,289,1842,1867]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Mercuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="corsensis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="75A9EA9EE604FF9DFF47A85E8444B130" box="[162,289,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">M. corsensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6E9A57E5E604FF9DFECDA85E8400B137" box="[296,357,1842,1868]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is about 
<quantity id="80259B69E604FF9DFE29A85E8743B130" box="[460,550,1841,1868]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="24" pageNumber="251" unit="km" value="220.0">220 km</quantity>
, the split of the two sister species must predate the younger pleistocene glaciation cycles, otherwise the large gap in the distribution areas can not be explained. In all circumstances today’s occurrences of both species must be considered as relicts of former larger distribution areas on both islands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4762368CE604FF9DFCC8AFBB8692B76A" blockId="24.[813,1415,215,273]" pageId="24" pageNumber="251">TAXA UNCERTAIN, INSUFFICIENTLY KNOWN OR CONFUSED</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
